1.2.2 - Instruction Set Architecture 

- ISA represents the view a programmer has of hardware and the knowledge needed to control the processor 
    
- Includes: 
    
    - Structure of programmable storage 
        
    - Instruction set and formats 
        
    - Methods for addressing and accessing data items 
        
    - Execution process (fetch execute and all that) 
        
- Has an assembly language 
    
    - Low level with a one-one correspondence with machine code 
        

1.2.6 - Assembly to Machine Code 

- Looking at MIPS 
    
- Three types of instructions 
    
- 32 registers 
    
    - $zero (stores 0) 
        
    - $s0, $s1 …. $s7 (10000, 10001, … , 10111 or 16-23) 
        
    - $t0, $t1 …. $t7 (01000, 01001, … , 01111 or 8-15) 
        

1.2.7 - I-type Instructions 

 (GET THE PHOTO FROM ONENOTE)

- Opcode is the instruction code 
    
- Rs is the source register 
    
- Rd is the destination register 
    
- Address is a memory address or constant 
    

1.2.8 - R-type Instructions 

![Fig. II: format, of an](data:image/png;base64,)

- Opcode is the instruction code 
    
- Rs1 is the first source register 
    
- Rs2 is the second source register 
    
- Rd is the destination register 
    
- Shift is a shift amount for shift instructions 
    
- Funct is a supplement for opcode for certain instructions
